1.8 Example 1.9

1.8.1 Load data

patent_ts &lt;- 
  read_excel("data/J02.xlsx") |&gt; 
  rename(cnt = `#patents`) |&gt; 
  as_tsibble(index = year)



1.8.2 Time series cross-validation
To create one-step forecast in historical data, you need to set up time series cross-validation. Great explanation is provided in Forecasting: Principles and Practice by Rob J Hyndman and George Athanasopoulos.
Call stretch_tsibble() to construct time series cross-validation that each training set is defined by .id, which is used as a key in the output tsibble object. Apply filter(.id != max(.id)) to exclude the last set that entire data is used as training data.

patent_cv &lt;- 
  patent_ts |&gt; 
  stretch_tsibble(.step = 1, .init = 7) |&gt; 
  filter(.id != max(.id))

patent_cv

# A tsibble: 255 x 3 [1Y]
# Key:       .id [17]
    year   cnt   .id
   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;int&gt;
 1  1993  21.5     1
 2  1994  28.6     1
 3  1995  59.2     1
 4  1996  68.4     1
 5  1997  67.3     1
 6  1998  50.6     1
 7  1999  56       1
 8  1993  21.5     2
 9  1994  28.6     2
10  1995  59.2     2
# ℹ 245 more rows




1.8.3 Models
Let us use Holt’s linear method with optimized initialization and smoothing parameters. As a result, it will return one model object per each cross-validation set.

fit_cv &lt;- 
  patent_cv |&gt; 
  model(
    Holt = ETS(cnt ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("N"))
  )

fit_cv

# A mable: 17 x 2
# Key:     .id [17]
     .id         Holt
   &lt;int&gt;      &lt;model&gt;
